<li id="cite_note-110"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-110">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1215172403"><cite id="CITEREFPratt1853" class="citation book cs1">Pratt, Parley (1853). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://archive.org/stream/seereditedbyorso01unse#page/158/mode/1up"><i>The Seer</i></a>. Washington, D.C. Liverpool Orson Pratt Franklin D. Richards. p.&#160;158,172<span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">October 9,</span> 2017</span>. <q>Inasmuch as God was the first husband to her, it may be that He only gave her to be the wife of Joseph while in this mortal state, and that He intended after the resurrection to again take her as one of his wives to raise up immortal spirits in eternity. ... We have now clearly shown that God the Father had a plurality of wives, one or more being in eternity by whom He begat our spirits as well as the spirit of Jesus His First Born, and another being upon the earth by whom He begat the tabernacle of Jesus.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=The+Seer&amp;rft.pages=158%2C172&amp;rft.pub=Washington%2C+D.C.+Liverpool+Orson+Pratt+Franklin+D.+Richards&amp;rft.date=1853&amp;rft.aulast=Pratt&amp;rft.aufirst=Parley&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Farchive.org%2Fstream%2Fseereditedbyorso01unse%23page%2F158%2Fmode%2F1up&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AOrigin+of+Latter+Day+Saint+polygamy" class="Z3988"></span></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-111"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-111">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1215172403"><cite id="CITEREFDana2004" class="citation book cs1">Dana, Bruce E. (September 2004). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=-z8NVySmnmcC&amp;pg=PA62"><i>The Eternal Father and His Son</i></a>. Cedar Fort Inc. p.&#160;62. <a href="/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" class="mw-redirect" title="ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/1555177883" title="Special:BookSources/1555177883"><bdi>1555177883</bdi></a><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">October 9,</span> 2017</span>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=The+Eternal+Father+and+His+Son&amp;rft.pages=62&amp;rft.pub=Cedar+Fort+Inc.&amp;rft.date=2004-09&amp;rft.isbn=1555177883&amp;rft.aulast=Dana&amp;rft.aufirst=Bruce+E.&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3D-z8NVySmnmcC%26pg%3DPA62&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AOrigin+of+Latter+Day+Saint+polygamy" class="Z3988"></span></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-Desert-112"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-Desert_112-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Desert_112-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Desert_112-2"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Desert_112-3"><sup><i><b>d</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1215172403"><cite id="CITEREFSchelling_Durham1997" class="citation book cs1">Schelling Durham, Michael (1997). <span class="id-lock-registration" title="Free registration required"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://archive.org/details/desertbetweenmou0000durh"><i>Desert Between the Mountains: Mormons, Miners, Padres, Mountain Men, and the Opening of the Great Basin, 1772â1869</i></a></span> (1st&#160;ed.). New York City: Henry Holt &amp; Company, Inc. p.&#160;<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://archive.org/details/desertbetweenmou0000durh/page/182">182</a>. <a href="/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" class="mw-redirect" title="ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/9780805041613" title="Special:BookSources/9780805041613"><bdi>9780805041613</bdi></a>. <q>Pratt clearly loud out arguments in favor of polygamy that the Saints would use for years to come. ... Pratt and others argued that Jesus had three wives: Mary Magdalene, and Lazarus' two sisters, Mary and Martha. Orson Hyde went a step further and preached that 'Jesus Christ was married at Cana of Galilee, that Mary, Martha, and others were his wives, and that he begat children.'<span class="cs1-kern-right"></span></q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Desert+Between+the+Mountains%3A+Mormons%2C+Miners%2C+Padres%2C+Mountain+Men%2C+and+the+Opening+of+the+Great+Basin%2C+1772%E2%80%931869&amp;rft.place=New+York+City&amp;rft.pages=182&amp;rft.edition=1st&amp;rft.pub=Henry+Holt+%26+Company%2C+Inc.&amp;rft.date=1997&amp;rft.isbn=9780805041613&amp;rft.aulast=Schelling+Durham&amp;rft.aufirst=Michael&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Farchive.org%2Fdetails%2Fdesertbetweenmou0000durh&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AOrigin+of+Latter+Day+Saint+polygamy" class="Z3988"></span></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-113"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-113">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1215172403"><cite id="CITEREFSwanson2013" class="citation book cs1">Swanson, Vern G. (2013). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=Rss1CgAAQBAJ&amp;pg=PT251">"Christ and Polygamy"</a>. <i>Dynasty of the Holy Grail: Mormonism's Holy Bloodline</i>. Springville, UT: Cedar Fort, Inc. pp.&#160;247â259. <a href="/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" class="mw-redirect" title="ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/9781462104048" title="Special:BookSources/9781462104048"><bdi>9781462104048</bdi></a>. <q>Dr. William E. Phipps noted that the belief that 'Jesus married, and married often!' was used to encourage and promote the doctrine of polygamy amongst timid Latter-Day Saints ... By the late-1850s the idea that more than one woman was married to Jesus was widely accepted among Mormon circles. ... As if the concept of Christ's polygamy was not unsettling enough, Mormonism even taught in the nineteenth century that God the Father had a plurality of wives as well.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.atitle=Christ+and+Polygamy&amp;rft.btitle=Dynasty+of+the+Holy+Grail%3A+Mormonism%27s+Holy+Bloodline&amp;rft.place=Springville%2C+UT&amp;rft.pages=247-259&amp;rft.pub=Cedar+Fort%2C+Inc.&amp;rft.date=2013&amp;rft.isbn=9781462104048&amp;rft.aulast=Swanson&amp;rft.aufirst=Vern+G.&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DRss1CgAAQBAJ%26pg%3DPT251&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AOrigin+of+Latter+Day+Saint+polygamy" class="Z3988"></span></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-114"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-114">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1215172403"><cite id="CITEREFGrant1853" class="citation journal cs1">Grant, Jedediah (August 7, 1853). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=A18tAAAAYAAJ&amp;pg=PA345">"Uniformity"</a>. <i>Journal of Discourses</i>. <b>1</b>: 345â346. <q><span class="cs1-kern-left"></span>'The grand reason why the Gentiles and philosophers of his school persecuted Jesus Christ, was, because he had so many wives; there were Elizabeth, and Mary, and a host of others that followed him.' ... The grand reason of the burst of public sentiment in anathemas upon Christ and his disciples, causing his crucifixion, was evidently based upon polygamy, according to the testimony of the philosophers who rose in that age.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Journal+of+Discourses&amp;rft.atitle=Uniformity&amp;rft.volume=1&amp;rft.pages=345-346&amp;rft.date=1853-08-07&amp;rft.aulast=Grant&amp;rft.aufirst=Jedediah&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DA18tAAAAYAAJ%26pg%3DPA345&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AOrigin+of+Latter+Day+Saint+polygamy" class="Z3988"></span></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-115"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-115">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1215172403"><cite id="CITEREFPratt1853" class="citation journal cs1">Pratt, Orson (October 1853). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://archive.org/stream/seereditedbyorso01unse#page/158/mode/1up">"The Seer"</a>. <i>The Seer</i>. <b>1</b> (10): 158,172<span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">October 9,</span> 2017</span>. <q>Inasmuch as God was the first husband to her, it may be that He only gave her to be the wife of Joseph while in this mortal state, and that He intended after the resurrection to again take her as one of his wives to raise up immortal spirits in eternity. ... We have now clearly shown that God the Father had a plurality of wives, one or more being in eternity by whom He begat our spirits as well as the spirit of Jesus His First Born, and another being upon the earth by whom He begat the tabernacle of Jesus.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=The+Seer&amp;rft.atitle=The+Seer&amp;rft.volume=1&amp;rft.issue=10&amp;rft.pages=158%2C172&amp;rft.date=1853-10&amp;rft.aulast=Pratt&amp;rft.aufirst=Orson&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Farchive.org%2Fstream%2Fseereditedbyorso01unse%23page%2F158%2Fmode%2F1up&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AOrigin+of+Latter+Day+Saint+polygamy" class="Z3988"></span></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-116"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-116">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1215172403"><cite id="CITEREFDana2004" class="citation book cs1">Dana, Bruce E. (September 2004). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=-z8NVySmnmcC&amp;pg=PA62"><i>The Eternal Father and His Son</i></a>. Cedar Fort Inc. p.&#160;62. <a href="/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" class="mw-redirect" title="ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/1555177883" title="Special:BookSources/1555177883"><bdi>1555177883</bdi></a><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">October 9,</span> 2017</span>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=The+Eternal+Father+and+His+Son&amp;rft.pages=62&amp;rft.pub=Cedar+Fort+Inc.&amp;rft.date=2004-09&amp;rft.isbn=1555177883&amp;rft.aulast=Dana&amp;rft.aufirst=Bruce+E.&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3D-z8NVySmnmcC%26pg%3DPA62&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AOrigin+of+Latter+Day+Saint+polygamy" class="Z3988"></span></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-117"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-117">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1215172403"><cite id="CITEREFPratt1853" class="citation book cs1">Pratt, Orson (1853). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://archive.org/stream/seereditedbyorso01unse#page/159/mode/1up"><i>The Seer</i></a>. Washington, D.C. Liverpool Orson Pratt Franklin D. Richards. p.&#160;159,172<span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">October 9,</span> 2017</span>. <q>If all the acts of Jesus were written, we should no doubt learn that these beloved women [Mary, and Martha her sister, and Mary Magdalene] were his wives. ... We have also proved most clearly that the Son followed the example of his Father, and became the great Bridegroom to whom kings' daughters and many honorable Wives were to be married.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=The+Seer&amp;rft.pages=159%2C172&amp;rft.pub=Washington%2C+D.C.+Liverpool+Orson+Pratt+Franklin+D.+Richards&amp;rft.date=1853&amp;rft.aulast=Pratt&amp;rft.aufirst=Orson&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Farchive.org%2Fstream%2Fseereditedbyorso01unse%23page%2F159%2Fmode%2F1up&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AOrigin+of+Latter+Day+Saint+polygamy" class="Z3988"></span></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-118"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-118">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1215172403"><cite id="CITEREFHyde1854" class="citation journal cs1">Hyde, Orson (October 6, 1854). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://contentdm.lib.byu.edu/digital/collection/JournalOfDiscourses3/id/7970">"The Marriage Relations"</a>. <i>Journal of Discourses</i>. <b>2</b>: 81â82. <q>Jesus was the bridegroom at the marriage at Cana of Galilee ... I do not despise to be called ... a child of the Savior if he had Mary, Martha, and several others as wives ... I shall say here, that before the Savior died, he looked upon his own natural children ....</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Journal+of+Discourses&amp;rft.atitle=The+Marriage+Relations&amp;rft.volume=2&amp;rft.pages=81-82&amp;rft.date=1854-10-06&amp;rft.aulast=Hyde&amp;rft.aufirst=Orson&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fcontentdm.lib.byu.edu%2Fdigital%2Fcollection%2FJournalOfDiscourses3%2Fid%2F7970&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AOrigin+of+Latter+Day+Saint+polygamy" class="Z3988"></span></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-119"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-119">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1215172403"><cite id="CITEREFHyde1855" class="citation journal cs1">Hyde, Orson (March 18, 1855). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=dUMEAAAAQAAJ&amp;q=martha">"The Judgements of God on the United StatesâThe Saints and the World"</a>. <i>Journal of Discourses</i>. <b>2</b>: 210. <q>... Jesus Christ was married at Cana of Galilee, that Mary, Martha, and others were his wives, and that he begat children.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Journal+of+Discourses&amp;rft.atitle=The+Judgements+of+God+on+the+United+States%E2%80%94The+Saints+and+the+World&amp;rft.volume=2&amp;rft.pages=210&amp;rft.date=1855-03-18&amp;rft.aulast=Hyde&amp;rft.aufirst=Orson&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DdUMEAAAAQAAJ%26q%3Dmartha&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AOrigin+of+Latter+Day+Saint+polygamy" class="Z3988"></span></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-120"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-120">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1215172403"><cite id="CITEREFHyde1857" class="citation journal cs1">Hyde, Orson (March 1857). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://contentdm.lib.byu.edu/digital/collection/JournalOfDiscourses3/id/500/rec/1">"Man the Head of the WomanâKingdom of GodâThe Seed of ChristâPolygamyâSociety in Utah"</a>. <i>Journal of Discourses</i>. <b>4</b>: 259. <q>It will be borne in mind that once on a time, there was a marriage in Cana of Galilee; and on a careful reading of that transaction, it will be discovered that no less a person than Jesus Christ was married on that occasion. If he was never married, his intimacy with Mary and Martha, and the other Mary also whom Jesus loved, must have been highly unbecoming and improper to say the best of it.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Journal+of+Discourses&amp;rft.atitle=Man+the+Head+of+the+Woman%E2%80%94Kingdom+of+God%E2%80%94The+Seed+of+Christ%E2%80%94Polygamy%E2%80%94Society+in+Utah&amp;rft.volume=4&amp;rft.pages=259&amp;rft.date=1857-03&amp;rft.aulast=Hyde&amp;rft.aufirst=Orson&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fcontentdm.lib.byu.edu%2Fdigital%2Fcollection%2FJournalOfDiscourses3%2Fid%2F500%2Frec%2F1&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AOrigin+of+Latter+Day+Saint+polygamy" class="Z3988"></span></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-121"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-121">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1215172403"><cite id="CITEREFBarry1910" class="citation journal cs1">Barry, Richard (October 1910). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=Pm8-AQAAMAAJ&amp;pg=PA446">"The Mormon Evasion of Anti-Polygamy Laws"</a>. <i>Pearson's Magazine</i>. <b>24</b> (4): 446.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Pearson%27s+Magazine&amp;rft.atitle=The+Mormon+Evasion+of+Anti-Polygamy+Laws&amp;rft.volume=24&amp;rft.issue=4&amp;rft.pages=446&amp;rft.date=1910-10&amp;rft.aulast=Barry&amp;rft.aufirst=Richard&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DPm8-AQAAMAAJ%26pg%3DPA446&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AOrigin+of+Latter+Day+Saint+polygamy" class="Z3988"></span></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-122"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-122">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1215172403"><cite id="CITEREFYoung1870" class="citation journal cs1">Young, Brigham (November 13, 1870). <a class="external text" href="https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/Journal_of_Discourses/Volume_13/Gathering_the_Poor%E2%80%94Religion_a_Science">"Gathering the PoorâReligion a Science"</a>. <i>Journal of Discourses</i>. <b>13</b>: 309. <q>The Scripture says that He, the Lord, came walking in the Temple, with His train; I do not know who they were, unless His wives and children; but at any rate they filled the Temple, and how many there were who could not get into the Temple I cannot say. This is the account given by Isaiah, whether he told the truth or not I leave every body to judge for himself.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Journal+of+Discourses&amp;rft.atitle=Gathering+the+Poor%E2%80%94Religion+a+Science&amp;rft.volume=13&amp;rft.pages=309&amp;rft.date=1870-11-13&amp;rft.aulast=Young&amp;rft.aufirst=Brigham&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fen.wikisource.org%2Fwiki%2FJournal_of_Discourses%2FVolume_13%2FGathering_the_Poor%25E2%2580%2594Religion_a_Science&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AOrigin+of+Latter+Day+Saint+polygamy" class="Z3988"></span></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-123"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-123">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1215172403"><cite class="citation journal cs1">"Evening Meeting". <i>Wilford Woodruff's Journal</i>. <b>8</b>: 187. July 22, 1883. <q>Joseph F. Smith ... He spoke upon the marriage on Cana of Galilee.  He thought Jesus was the Bridegroom and Mary and Martha the brides.  He also referred to Luke 10:34â42.  Also John 11:2â5, John 12:13.  Joseph Smith spoke upon these passages to show that Mary and Martha manifested much closer relationship then merely believer ....</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Wilford+Woodruff%27s+Journal&amp;rft.atitle=Evening+Meeting&amp;rft.volume=8&amp;rft.pages=187&amp;rft.date=1883-07-22&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AOrigin+of+Latter+Day+Saint+polygamy" class="Z3988"></span> Quote reproduced at <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://emp.byui.edu/huffr/rel%20372/may%20the%20source%20be%20with%20you.htm">byui.edu</a>.</span>
</li>
